It has been thought by some that he did not wish to express himself clearly lest his views, being opposed to the religious ideas of the time, call down persecu· tion upon him. But in the fragments of his writings that have come down to us he is singularly outspoken. And while his obscurity is often alluded to by the ancients, he is never charged by them with intent to be obscure. Lucretius, indeed, rather pays him a compli- ment by implying that heis difficult to understand only to the ‘light- minded’ Greeks.
